  <p>
    That said, we don't have third-party independent test results for every SKU we
    recommend. No sunscreen review site does. What we can say: these brands have track
    records, significant consumer review bases (1,800–31,000+ ratings), and no history
    of SPF mislabeling.
  </p>

  <h2>How to protect yourself</h2>
  <p>
    You can't independently test the SPF on your bottle. But you can take steps to
    reduce your exposure to the risk:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Favour brands with pharmacy distribution.</strong> Products sold through
      pharmacies (La Roche-Posay, EltaMD, CeraVe) face more routine regulatory scrutiny
      than DTC beauty brands.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Favour dermatologist-recommended brands.</strong> Derm endorsements aren't
      a guarantee, but clinical distribution creates accountability.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Apply more than you think you need.</strong> The SPF on the label is
      measured at 2mg/cm² of skin — most people apply a quarter of that. Even if your
      SPF 50 is delivering SPF 30, applying generously brings you closer to the label.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Reapply every two hours.</strong> Regardless of SPF level, all sunscreens
      degrade in UV light. A compromised or underapplied SPF 50 protects less than a
      correctly applied SPF 30 reapplied on time.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Be skeptical of very cheap, unestablished brands.</strong> The cost
      pressure that leads to mislabeling is most acute in low-margin, high-competition
      segments — exactly where white-label or budget SPFs live.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>The bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    The CHOICE scandal is a wake-up call about sunscreen integrity — but it doesn't mean
    sunscreen doesn't work. It means you should use brands with a track record, apply
    generously, and reapply. The products most at risk are budget SPFs from brands with
    no clinical history and no independent testing.
  </p>
